---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
// The About copy is Editor-authored; we embed it directly so the v0.1 build
// has no extra moving parts. Vini can switch this to a markdown-loader pattern
// later if more pages join.
---

<Base title="About — Madār" description="About Madār — an editorial publication on early childhood and K-12 education, written and made in English and Arabic." lang="en">

  <article class="about-page container">

    <header class="about-page__head">
      <p class="kicker">About</p>
      <h1 class="about-page__title">About Madār</h1>
      <p class="about-page__title-ar" lang="ar" dir="rtl">حول مدار</p>
    </header>

    <div class="about-page__body measure">

      <h2>What this is</h2>
      <p>
        Madār is an editorial publication about early childhood and K-12 education,
        written and made for readers who already take the subject seriously. We
        publish in English and in Arabic, with neither language treated as the
        translation of the other. The name means <em>orbit</em>: two languages held
        in one orbit, each with its own pull.
      </p>
      <p>
        We are not a magazine of news, and not an aggregator. We publish slowly, in
        small quantities, and we expect each piece to repay close reading. A reader
        who comes for the speed of a feed is in the wrong place; a reader who wants
        to know what a primary teacher actually does on Monday morning, in a named
        school, in a named country, is in the right one.
      </p>

      <h2>How we choose what to cover</h2>
      <p>
        The publication has an editorial posture, and it is the posture, not a
        geographic checklist, that determines what runs.
      </p>
      <p>
        We are interested in education as it is practiced — by teachers, by
        ministries, by parents, by the people inside school buildings — rather than
        as it is theorized at conferences. We are interested in the texture of a
        system: the salary band, the textbook procurement cycle, the bus route, the
        cooling budget, the language of instruction debate, the headteacher who has
        been in the role for fifteen years and remembers three reforms. We are
        interested in policy when policy is the right unit of analysis, and we are
        not interested in it when the right unit of analysis is a classroom.
      </p>
      <p>
        We follow stories that the international education conversation tends to
        discuss only in aggregate, or only when something has gone catastrophically
        wrong. A school year in which nothing collapses is, often, the story; a
        quiet reform that works is the story; a teacher's working week is the story.
        The publication exists in part because that kind of attention is rarely
        paid in either the English-language or the Arabic-language education press,
        and the absence is something we want to correct in small, specific ways —
        one piece at a time.
      </p>
      <p>
        We publish bilingually because the readers we want already live
        bilingually, and because the same education argument carries differently in
        Arabic than it does in English. A piece about a UAE cooling budget reads
        one way in English and another in Arabic; both readings are real, and both
        belong on the page. The bilingual close — a recurring stylistic device
        where a piece moves into a second language for its final register — is one
        of the publication's signatures.
      </p>
      <p>
        We work slowly because the alternative is to write the wrong piece quickly.
        A piece that needs another week to verify a salary figure gets another
        week. A piece that cannot pass the dignity check — the test of whether the
        people described would recognize themselves in our description of them —
        does not run.
      </p>

      <h2>How we write</h2>
      <p>A few conventions are visible in the pieces we publish, and worth naming.</p>
      <p>
        Pieces fall into three forms. <em>Curated</em> pieces are short readings of
        a single primary document or piece of local journalism, with our interpretation
        set against it — never a summary, never an aggregation. <em>Editorial</em>
        pieces are short original commentaries that argue a single claim from named
        sources. <em>Essays</em> are longer original works, weekly, with a thesis a
        reader could not have arrived at by skimming a press release.
      </p>
      <p>
        Some pieces end in two languages. We call this the bilingual close: the
        English argument has been made, and the closing register moves into Arabic,
        or Krio, or Spanish, or whichever language the people in the piece actually
        live in. The close is not decoration. We use it when the second language
        carries something the English cannot, and we refuse it when it would only
        signal cultural sensitivity to a reader who needs reassuring.
      </p>
      <p>
        A small number of our pieces use composite figures — invented stand-ins
        assembled from interviews and published reporting where no single person
        can be named for legitimate reasons. Where this is done, the name of the
        composite character carries a dagger (†) on its first appearance, and a
        short footnote at the foot of the piece, above the sources, names the
        convention. This is the lightest visible mark that still does the disclosure
        honestly, and it tells the reader, on the page, what they are reading.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every piece names a specific place, a specific time, and at least one named
        human being whose presence is not decorative. Every piece cites at least
        one primary source — a ministry document, a named educator quoted in a
        named publication, peer-reviewed work, local reporting — with a working
        link. Wikipedia is a starting point and never a citation.
      </p>

      <h2>What we refuse</h2>
      <p>A short register-list, written out so that no future contributor can claim it was not.</p>
      <p>
        We do not write in NGO-frame language. People in our pieces have professions
        and names; they are not <em>voices</em>, not <em>beneficiaries</em>, not
        <em>the underserved</em>. We do not use <em>stakeholders</em> when we mean
        parents, teachers, ministers, or regulators, and we do not use <em>solutions</em>
        when we mean policies, programmes, or arguments.
      </p>
      <p>
        We do not write the savior story. Pieces that frame local educators as
        needing rescue by international actors will not run, regardless of how
        moving the rescue is. We do not romanticize children — not their poverty,
        not their resilience, not their photogenic faces. The dignity check is the
        last thing every piece passes before it ships: would the people described
        recognize themselves?
      </p>
      <p>
        We do not write edtech booster copy. Madār is not a buyer's guide for
        products and not a cheerleader for technology in classrooms, and pieces
        written in that register will be sent back. We do not write in the language
        of strategy consultancies; <em>best practices</em>, <em>scalable models</em>,
        <em>outcomes-driven frameworks</em> are not phrases this publication uses
        without irony. And we do not exoticize. Specificity is the cure for
        exoticism, and specificity is what this publication trades in.
      </p>

      <h2>Who is making this</h2>
      <p>
        Madār is made by a small team led by its founder. Bylines on each piece
        name the editor and the designer for that piece. The founder's identity is
        not the publication's selling point; the publication is.
      </p>
      <p>
        Contact: <a href="mailto:hello@madar.example">hello@madar.example</a>
        (placeholder — production address to follow). A newsletter, English and
        Arabic, will open for sign-ups when v0.1 ships.
      </p>

      <h2>A note on Arabic</h2>
      <p>
        Arabic is not translation. It is the second register Madār operates in,
        equal in weight to the English, and some pieces are Arabic-first in their
        conception while others are English-first. The bilingual close, when it
        earns its place, is the mechanism by which the two registers meet on the
        page. A reader of either language should leave a Madār piece feeling that
        the publication has paid them the same attention.
      </p>

      <p class="about-page__close" lang="ar" dir="rtl">
        نكتب من مدار واحد بلغتين، ولكلٍ منهما وزنها الخاص.
      </p>

    </div>
  </article>

</Base>

<style>
  .about-page { padding-block: var(--space-lg) var(--space-2xl); }
  .about-page__head { padding-block: var(--space-xl) var(--space-lg); border-block-end: 1px solid var(--color-rule); margin-block-end: var(--space-lg); }
  .about-page__title { margin-block-start: var(--space-sm); max-width: 22ch; }
  .about-page__title-ar {
    margin-block-start: var(--space-sm);
    font-family: var(--font-arabic-display);
    font-size: 36px;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    opacity: 0.85;
  }
  .about-page__body h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: var(--fs-h2);
    line-height: var(--lh-h2);
    letter-spacing: var(--tr-h2);
    margin-block: 2.5rem 1rem;
  }
  .about-page__body h2::before {
    content: '';
    display: block;
    width: 38px;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--color-ink);
    margin-block-end: 0.85rem;
  }
  .about-page__body p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: var(--fs-body);
    line-height: var(--lh-body);
    margin-block: 0 1.2em;
  }
  .about-page__close {
    margin-block-start: 2.5rem;
    padding-block-start: 1.5rem;
    border-block-start: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
    font-family: var(--font-arabic-display);
    font-size: 22px;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    opacity: 0.92;
  }
</style>
